            "description": "",
            "details": "<p><em>Baḥr-i Fārs</em> (Persian Gulf): It is a sea that emerges from the northern side of the <em>Baḥr-i Hind</em> (Indian Ocean). To the east of <em>Mekrāntīz</em> (Makran coast region), at the source of the <em>Baḥr-i Fārs</em>, it appears visibly like a mouth (<em>dehān</em>). Likewise, the city of <em>‘Ummān</em> (Oman) is seen on the western side of this sea, and it too is discernible at its mouth, that is, its strait. From there it extends, running along the <em>‘Ummān</em> (Oman) coast, and from <em>‘Abbādān</em> (Abadan, Iran) to <em>Mehrūbān</em> (Mahrūbān, near modern Bushehr). Then it passes to <em>Sīnīz</em> (modern Bushehr/Old Siniz) and stretches southward until it reaches <em>Ḫayyābe</em> (Khabbah / Khaybah). From there it proceeds to <em>Seyfü’l-baḥr</em> (“the Sword of the Sea,” Fars coast), and to its east is <em>Sīrāf</em> (Siraf, Iran). From that point, it continues along broken mountain ranges and high desert passes and hills, and then, moving further east, it winds around to <em>Ḥıṣn Ibn ‘Ammāre</em> (Hisn Ibn ‘Ammāra) and reaches <em>Hürmüz</em> (Hormuz), which is the port of <em>Kirmān</em> (Kerman). After that, it stretches toward the southeastern direction, reaching the Makran coast and <em>Ḳaṣṣatīz</em>. [translation]</p>",
